content.description: Short, flaring crack easily seen as a lightning bolt shape from the approach to the area. From the base, climb easy terrain and make an awkward move into the crack. Once in the crack, and smear up to the anchors.
content.protection: Cams to 1.5" are most useful. Few constrictions for passive pro.
content.location: Easily seen from the approach. On the right side of the lowest slab to the right of Baby Steps.

content.description:
Fun and obvious slightly left leaning finger to hands crack with solid feet the entire way. Tops out through a v-slot gully about 6' right of the top rope hangers. It was mossy and slightly chossy, but I cleaned it up real nice.

Gear anchor recommended (BD 4 and 2 are handy) to belay up your second, since using the hangers belonging to the top rope options to climber's left will abrade your rope over the edge.
content.protection: Gear to 2.5", save a BD #4 and at least one #2 for the gear belay.
content.location: On the right side of Arnica Glen area (mentioned in Kramar guidebook, but not detailed), just right of a few top rope routes. It's just left of a chossy roof that I'll maybe lead another time...

content.description: IMO, the best of the 5.easy routes on the wall. Cruiser slab leads to a single bolt and then on to a 15' solid finger to hands crack about 2/3 of the way up. Hangers have pre-installed rap rings.
content.protection: Gear to BD #3, single bolt. 2 bolted hangers with rappel rings.
content.location: Far right route on the lower tier wall that contains Baby Steps, Baby's Behind, Damn Mounties, etc. Look for the single bolt about half way up just before the hill/ramp that leads to the Birthday Boy belay ledge.

content.description: Begin off a ledge with a big ponderosa pine tree, follow bolts.
content.protection: 8 quickdraws
content.location: All the way at the bottom left of playground point.

content.description: To the left of Birthday Boy is a new route with shiny bolts.  Careful clipping the first as there is no belay anchor on the small ledge. The route heads up and to the left over a small hood.   From here, staying to the left uses a single bolt and reduces difficulty.  Staying in line with the anchor uses 2 bolts, and increases the difficulty and rope drag. Use long draws at the hood to avoid rope substantial rope drag. A bit of runout to a shared anchor with Lunch Money.
content.protection: 7-8 bolts. Chains.
content.location: To the left of Birthday Boy.

content.description: Follow a nice flake to a small overlap leading to the slab above.
content.protection: 5 bolts
content.location: 3rd route from the left on the upper tier.

content.description: Easy slab to a one-move roof pull crux to more easy slab.  All the real moves are well protected.
content.protection: 5 bolts, chains
content.location: on the leftmost wall, identifiable by the big roof pull.  Easy to hike up and toprope.

content.description: Starting from the same precarious belay as Aisle of Sky, climb around the big flake to a high first bolt. Kramar says you can get a piece under the flake (up to 2") or just run out the easy first 30-40 feet. Climb a short arete leading to a fun mantle. Finish up on easy jugs to the anchors.
content.protection: 4ish bolts, anchors at top and bottom for belayer. Optional gear at the start up to 2".
content.location: Same as Aisle of Sky, just head left instead of straight up the slab.

content.description: Large flake at the start offers multiple interesting options.  Continue up the face for a more challenging climb, or simply use the flake system.  Crux is a small chossy roof at the top.
content.protection: 2 double-bolt anchors offer multiple top rope options.
content.location: Follow the obvious path right from Zap Crack start.  Trail will follow the rock face to a corner with the route's flake start.  Top rope approach can be done by continuing the steep trail right and up, but it is much easier going left of Baby Steps start, up the screen and to the right of Baby Steps top.

content.description: Follow the easy corner off the Birthday Boy Ledge
content.protection: Gear to 3", one bolt at the top that can be bypassed

content.description: A somewhat dirty climb left of Hopscotch.  May get cleaner with more ascents.
content.protection: Gear to 1".
content.location: Left climb on middle tier

content.description: Follow a right facing corner up to and past a bolt on the slabby finish.
content.protection: Gear to 2", 1 bolt.
content.location: Rigthmost route on upper tier.

content.description: A short fun route up the right-facing corner right of Father's Day. Follow up to the roof where a large jug makes clipping the bolt a breeze. Continue over the roof up to the anchors on solid holds.
content.protection: 2 bolts.  A 2" or 3" cam could be placed between the bolts.
content.location: 2nd route from the left on the upper tier.

content.description: A nice beginner route of the middle tier with good protection.
content.protection: 5 bolts
content.location: middle tier

content.description: Follow edges up the center of the large partially detached block.
content.protection: Three bolts with potential for a grounder at the second bolt.
content.location: Left most route on the top tier.

content.description: Easy slab climbing with decent protection. It’s a bit dirty and wandering. Consider running out some of the slab to make the route more straight.
content.protection: Gear to 1”. Two bolts on the route. Two bolts + chains at the top.
content.location: Crack and slab system just to the right of Baby Steps (which is the first bolts you come to on the trail from the parking lot). Chains are to the right of the blocky rocks you see to the right of the top of Baby Steps.

content.description:
Traverses right under the roof above the anchors for Baby Steps/Baby's Behind/Damn Mounties/etc. into a fun lieback flake and finishes at the base of the landing about 40' back from Hopscotch and Leapfrog. Some fun and tricky moves at the end of the roof to pull onto the flake!

Extend all your gear- especially under the roof, as there's quite a bit of unavoidable rope drag.
content.protection: Gear to BD # 3. Two bolt anchor, no links or chains (bolted 7/13/20).
content.location: Climb Baby Steps, Baby's Behind, or Damn Mounties to get onto the belay ledge. From there, 'Busted Flat is the roof directly above you and the chossy ramp that gains the bench with Hopscotch and Leapfrog.

content.description: climb a short crack and pull over the blocky to a ledge with anchors.
content.protection: Gear to 2", one bolt
content.location: a few minutes walk from the top of Playground Point, on the way to Whutza Point

content.description: Probably the best route in the area.  Head up the slab to the roof, move right into a corner at the base of the basalt flake.  Climb past the flake and up the arete to the anchors.
content.protection: 8 bolts
content.location: On a slab uphill and 100 ft left Baby Steps.

content.description: Easy route with plenty of good stance to place gear. This route is really that easy that a 5 year old baby top-roped this with no issues. Aptly named.
content.protection: Gear to 1 inches in the lower half. Upper half has two bolts. Has bolted anchors at top with rap rings.
content.location: This is left of the fully bolted route called Baby Steps.

content.description: Belay on a very small ledge (2-4") with a pair of bolts. Move left from the belay, moving along the flake until you come to the first bolt. Clip and pull up onto the slab and then continue up the easy, but pure friction slab climbing for the next 2-3 bolts. Move into some big jugs for the final section of the route to the top.
content.protection: 6 bolts plus chain anchors at top. A pair of bolts at the bottom for the belayer. Scramble off to the climbers right or rap.
content.location: 100-150' left of Baby steps. Traverse across a small ledge to reach the belay bolts.
